WEBVTT

00:06.300 --> 00:08.291
*

00:20.280 --> 00:22.544
What do you think?

00:22.590 --> 00:24.683
Not your color.
Pretty sure this is

00:24.720 --> 00:27.188
the only color that
platypus skulls come in.

00:27.220 --> 00:29.120
I'll take it.

00:29.160 --> 00:31.458
Aanay, told you, it's
not for me, it's for Sherlock.

00:31.490 --> 00:33.219
He's into stuff like this.

00:33.260 --> 00:35.319
You name a kid something
like Sherlock, you pretty much

00:35.360 --> 00:37.123
guarantee he's gonna be
into stuff like that.

00:37.170 --> 00:39.593
Actually, his name is
the least odd thing about him.

00:39.640 --> 00:42.165
I'm gonna have to introduce you
one of these days.

00:42.210 --> 00:46.169
I'm hoping this little guy
will distract him for a while.

00:46.210 --> 00:47.768
He's been bored.

00:47.810 --> 00:50.779
No interesting murder cases
in the last couple of weeks.

00:50.810 --> 00:53.643
Oh, poor thing.
(laughs)

00:56.150 --> 01:00.553
You know, if you guys
are really looking for
something to do...

01:00.590 --> 01:02.820
Yeah?
(sighs) Nothing. It's
embarrassing, actually.

01:02.860 --> 01:05.624
Oh, is it?
Look, I was thinking
about you last week

01:05.660 --> 01:08.493
and I was gonna
call you, and I...

01:08.530 --> 01:11.624
I'm trying to find a guy
that I lost track of.

01:11.670 --> 01:12.694
Uh-huh.

01:12.740 --> 01:15.766
A one-night stand.
(gasps)

01:15.800 --> 01:19.236
Jennifer Sayles!

01:19.280 --> 01:22.306
I met him_ after one of our
girls' nights, actually.

01:22.350 --> 01:25.399
Do you remember, like,
a year ago, drinks in Midtown,

01:25.450 --> 01:26.849
and you bailed early?

01:26.880 --> 01:29.849
Well, I ended up at this
little bar on 42nd,

01:29.890 --> 01:31.846
and... I met Tony.

01:31.890 --> 01:34.688
Okay, does Tony
have a last name?

01:34.720 --> 01:36.585
Look, I know that he's
a photojournalist,

01:36.630 --> 01:40.452
I know that he is amazing
and that we just clicked.

01:40.500 --> 01:43.196
It wasn't just a drunken thing.
It wasn't, I'm telling you.

01:43.230 --> 01:45.391
After the bar, we went
to a gallery opening,

01:45.430 --> 01:47.534
and then we ended up
back at my place.

01:47.570 --> 01:50.607
The whole night, it
was just... perfect.

01:50.640 --> 01:52.608
It was like a movie.

01:52.640 --> 01:54.801
Except he had a flight
first thing in the morning.

01:54.840 --> 01:57.741
Some job in Paris
for a couple of months.

01:57.780 --> 01:59.543
We didn't even
exchange numbers.

01:59.580 --> 02:01.445
Jen, I have to be honest.

02:01.480 --> 02:03.880
I mean, if all you have
is a first name,

02:03.920 --> 02:05.888
I don't even know
where I'd begin.

02:05.920 --> 02:09.151
Anyway, this isn't
the kind of thing
that Sherlock and I do.

02:09.190 --> 02:11.556
Yeah, but you're great
at this, right?

02:11.590 --> 02:14.889
You're great at it,
and, Joan, I swear,

02:14.930 --> 02:18.627
I would never, ever
ask you to help me with
something so mortifying

02:18.670 --> 02:21.798
if I didn't think that this guy
might really be the one.

02:24.470 --> 02:26.506
HOLMES:
What you are describing
is not a case, it is

02:26.540 --> 02:28.804
a wild goose chase, only at
the end of a proper goose chase

02:28.840 --> 02:30.705
you get to eat a delicious
goose-- in this instance,

02:30.750 --> 02:33.241
your friend gets to find out
that some sweaty Lothario

02:33.280 --> 02:34.770
is not the man
of her dreams.

02:34.820 --> 02:36.685
Do you want to
help me or not?

02:36.720 --> 02:39.450
You are a consulting detective,
you are my partner.

02:39.490 --> 02:41.708
The work you are describing
falls somewhere between

02:41.760 --> 02:44.854
photographing philandering
spouses and finding a lost cat.

02:44.890 --> 02:46.858
I urge you to have
some professional pride.

02:46.900 --> 02:50.290
I do. Okay, she's my friend,
and she asked me for my help.

02:50.330 --> 02:52.833
Anyway, it's not like we have
anything better to work on.

02:52.870 --> 02:55.191
We have cold cases,
dozens of them.

02:55.240 --> 02:56.798
You have been looking
at these for days,

02:56.840 --> 02:59.400
and so far the only things
you have solved are the theft

02:59.440 --> 03:01.203
of a penny-farthing bicycle
and a nonfatal arson case

03:01.240 --> 03:02.798
which is older than my father.

03:02.850 --> 03:04.977
You have not left the house
In a week,

03:05.010 --> 03:08.616
and you're beginning to smell
like old mimeographs.
Be that as it may,

03:08.650 --> 03:10.618
I'm quite certain
that we can do better

03:10.650 --> 03:12.811
than helping your friend
find an MIA pickup artist.

03:12.860 --> 03:14.851
_ How?
Sometimes, Watson,

03:14.890 --> 03:17.381
when one wants a diamond,
one must resort

03:17.430 --> 03:19.557
to digging in a diamond mine.

03:19.600 --> 03:22.296
(Holmes sniffs)

03:22.330 --> 03:26.289
WATSON: For future reference,
a morgue is not a diamond mine.

03:26.340 --> 03:27.932
It's better.

03:27.970 --> 03:31.360
Diamonds are just pressed coal;
corpses have stories, secrets.

03:31.410 --> 03:33.628
(low groan) You said
you had an "in" here.

03:33.680 --> 03:37.309
A certain deputy medical
examiner who can be relied
upon to allow me access.

03:37.350 --> 03:39.739
And he's okay with letting
a civilian waltz in here

03:39.780 --> 03:42.613
to shop for a wrongful
death he might have
missed because...?

03:42.650 --> 03:44.948
Because he's so competitive,
it borders on illness.

03:44.990 --> 03:46.787
Let me guess--

03:46.820 --> 03:49.823
somebody wants
an ass-kicking?

03:49.860 --> 03:51.384
First time for everything,
I suppose.

03:54.500 --> 03:56.718
This is Joan Watson,
my partner.

03:56.770 --> 03:58.920
This is Dr. Eugene Hawes,
my sparring partner.

03:58.970 --> 04:01.837
Oh, it's nice to meet you.
You, too.

04:01.870 --> 04:03.007
Usual stakes?

04:03.040 --> 04:06.476
My cash against your corpses.

04:10.910 --> 04:12.002
(scoffs)

04:12.050 --> 04:13.574
Ponziani?
You think you can

04:13.620 --> 04:15.645
come in here with
that weak stuff?

04:19.660 --> 04:22.629
0 for 19-- I think
it's time to call it a day.

04:22.660 --> 04:24.355
I'm seriously starving,
and that is something

04:24.390 --> 04:25.880
that should not be
happening in here.

04:25.930 --> 04:27.795
Well, there's
a vending machine
down the hall,

04:27.830 --> 04:30.628
and at least a dozen
more bodies, so we
have the makings

04:30.670 --> 04:32.535
of a lovely evening.

04:38.070 --> 04:41.369
Right, this is Leo... Banin.

04:41.410 --> 04:43.401
Killed when his motorcycle

04:43.450 --> 04:45.645
veered across
the yellow line

04:45.680 --> 04:48.410
into an oncoming
minivan.

04:48.450 --> 04:51.783
The driver of that vehicle,
a Melissa Aguire...

04:51.820 --> 04:53.811
was also killed.

04:53.860 --> 04:55.384
Nope, there's no mystery there.

04:55.420 --> 04:57.024
The head wound is
the cause of death

04:57.060 --> 05:00.291
and the reason
we have helmet laws.

05:01.930 --> 05:03.864
We have a case.
Sherlock,

05:03.900 --> 05:05.720
nobody killed this man.

05:05.770 --> 05:08.591
No. But the day he died,

05:08.640 --> 05:10.858
he murdered someone else.

05:47.810 --> 05:50.506
You know, we got a lot
going on here. We always do.

05:50.550 --> 05:51.847
If you're looking
for entertainment,

05:51.880 --> 05:54.576
you don't need to go
shopping at the morgue.

05:54.620 --> 05:57.043
I reviewed your open cases--
Sisyphean drudge work.

05:57.090 --> 05:59.615
Nothing half as interesting
as what we have found.

05:59.660 --> 06:01.582
A traffic fatality?

06:01.620 --> 06:03.383
A professional hit man.

06:03.430 --> 06:05.921
His driver's license
identified him as Leo Banin.

06:05.960 --> 06:07.518
According to
his obituary,

06:07.560 --> 06:09.721
he was happily married,
a deacon at his church,

06:09.770 --> 06:11.920
and an RN at a retirement home.

06:11.970 --> 06:13.767
HOLMES: But before
that, he was a member

06:13.800 --> 06:16.064
of the Rukovskaya Bratva.

06:16.100 --> 06:18.807
No_te their_ distinctive
eight-pomted star.

06:18.840 --> 06:21.934
Detective Bell was kind enough
to run Mr. Banin's fingerprints

06:21.980 --> 06:23.948
through the international
database. Leo Banin

06:23.980 --> 06:26.744
started life as Vitaly Andropov,

06:26.780 --> 06:28.645
an assassin for the Bratva's

06:28.680 --> 06:30.944
Polish outfit. Interpol
believes him responsible

06:30.990 --> 06:32.548
for a string
of gruesome killings

06:32.590 --> 06:35.684
in the Warsaw Wesola district
dating back to 2005.

06:35.720 --> 06:37.426
Later that year,
Leo Banin

06:37.460 --> 06:38.825
sprang into existence.

06:38.860 --> 06:40.953
He began a quiet life
as a nurse in Queens,

06:41.000 --> 06:43.195
got married shortly thereafter,
hasn't been heard from since.

06:43.230 --> 06:44.822
GREGSON:
Well, that makes sense.

06:44.870 --> 06:47.191
When you get tired
of killing people in Warsaw,

06:47.240 --> 06:49.538
you retire to a place
like Jackson Heights.

06:49.570 --> 06:51.435
HOLMES: I don't believe
he did retire.

06:51.470 --> 06:53.472
At least not permanently.

06:55.140 --> 06:57.540
These cuts on the
side of his palms,

06:57.580 --> 06:59.207
they are uniform, a
perfect matched pair.

06:59.250 --> 07:01.571
He was wearing gloves when he
lost control of his motorcycle

07:01.620 --> 07:03.178
and slammed into
oncoming traffIc.

07:03.220 --> 07:05.984
I don't think that those
are a result of the crash.

07:06.020 --> 07:07.851
I once apprehended
a serial killer

07:07.890 --> 07:09.755
in Kensington who
strung his guitar

07:09.790 --> 07:11.451
with six different
murder weapons.

07:11.490 --> 07:14.493
He had scars on his hands
very Similar to those.

07:14.530 --> 07:15.895
Leo's wounds are raw.

07:15.930 --> 07:18.990
I think he garroted someone
the day he died.

07:19.030 --> 07:22.033
Well, not a bad bet, considering
that was his MO. in Warsaw.

07:22.070 --> 07:24.163
Oh, and now in New York.

07:24.210 --> 07:26.678
Whoever he killed, do you think
he did it on Bratva's orders?

07:26.710 --> 07:27.870
That's one possibility.

07:27.910 --> 07:29.002
There's just one problem.

07:29.040 --> 07:30.598
Unless you have
a garroted corpse

07:30.650 --> 07:32.049
I'm not aware of,

07:32.080 --> 07:33.217
you don't have a victim.

07:33.250 --> 07:35.013
If you don't have a corpse

07:35.050 --> 07:36.745
or a missing persons report,
you don't have a case.

07:36.790 --> 07:38.212
Which is precisely why

07:38.250 --> 07:40.480
we intend to speak to
the assassinurse's wife.

07:40.520 --> 07:41.657
We're hoping she
might be able

07:41.690 --> 07:43.681
to cast some light
on the situation.

07:43.730 --> 07:46.619
Of course I knew the tattoo.

07:46.660 --> 07:51.666
I knew he came here to get away
from an unhappy life in Poland.

07:51.700 --> 07:53.839
A bad life.

07:53.870 --> 07:55.531
I didn't know he...

07:55.570 --> 07:58.630
I can't believe Leo
was a killer.

07:58.670 --> 08:02.231
Were you aware of his
real name-- Vitaly?

08:02.280 --> 08:05.044
His name, to me, was Leo.

08:05.080 --> 08:07.514
That was his real name.

08:07.550 --> 08:10.110
Can you think of anyone that
your husband may have...

08:10.150 --> 08:11.617
wanted to harm?

08:11.650 --> 08:13.515
Someone he'd argued with?

08:13.560 --> 08:15.516
You don't know my husband.

08:15.560 --> 08:18.620
Talk to our neighbors,
our friends.

08:18.660 --> 08:20.150
He was a wonderful man.

08:20.200 --> 08:22.566
An hour before
the accident,

08:22.600 --> 08:27.162
he called me to
say he loved me.

08:27.200 --> 08:29.737
Did he give you
that necklace?

08:31.910 --> 08:34.174
We met at the church.

08:35.210 --> 08:37.178
Whatever you say

08:37.210 --> 08:40.008
my husband was,
that was the past.

08:40.050 --> 08:42.939
Finding God changed him.

08:42.990 --> 08:46.187
I see he got a medical
administration degree

08:46.220 --> 08:48.017
a year ago.

08:48.060 --> 08:50.324
MRS. BANIN:
It was our dream to open

08:50.360 --> 08:53.056
a senior care center.

08:54.260 --> 08:56.296
He had partners to help.

08:56.330 --> 08:58.924
We were finding investors.

08:58.970 --> 09:01.791
This was his life.

09:02.840 --> 09:05.809
Respectfully, Mrs. Banin...

09:05.840 --> 09:10.140
your husband was
a killer in Poland.

09:10.180 --> 09:13.149
A few days ago,
he killed again.

09:13.180 --> 09:14.977
When the one
that you love

09:15.020 --> 09:17.113
is revealed to
have a dark heart,

09:17.150 --> 09:20.256
it is...

09:20.290 --> 09:22.622
well, it's excruciating.

09:23.890 --> 09:27.121
I speak from experience.

09:29.400 --> 09:32.858
The shock will burn off.

09:36.770 --> 09:39.261
If there is anything
that you can tell us

09:39.310 --> 09:42.131
about who your husband
may have killed,

09:42.180 --> 09:44.273
helping us find
that person,

09:44.310 --> 09:49.145
that is an excellent way to
begin to repair yourself.

09:51.190 --> 09:52.748
I'm sorry.

09:54.320 --> 09:57.027
I cannot help you.

09:59.090 --> 10:01.650
HOLMES (lisping): This message
is for Travis Hardwick.

10:01.700 --> 10:03.167
This is Manny Tarkanian.

10:03.200 --> 10:06.294
I have a huge renovation;
it needs to move fast.

10:06.330 --> 10:08.890
I hear that you're
the best builder in Queens.

10:08.940 --> 10:11.408
I'm gonna text you
my contact information.

10:11.440 --> 10:14.307
Please... please get in touch.
Thank you.

10:14.340 --> 10:18.140
Who is Manny Tarkanian, and
why does he have a lisp?

10:18.180 --> 10:19.738
Childhood sledding accident.

10:19.780 --> 10:21.645
But let's not get caught up
in the backstory

10:21.680 --> 10:23.181
of a passing alias.
The question you should

10:23.220 --> 10:25.040
be asking is:
who is Travis Hardwick?

10:25.090 --> 10:26.216
I don't need to ask.

10:26.250 --> 10:28.059
You're gonna
tell me anyway.

10:28.090 --> 10:29.182
Let's begin
with two givens.

10:29.220 --> 10:31.188
Firstly, 76%
of all murder victims

10:31.230 --> 10:33.027
know their assailant.
We, as a speCIes,

10:33.060 --> 10:35.790
we tend to be killed
by the people closest to us--

10:35.830 --> 10:37.764
our friends, our spouses,
business associates.

10:37.800 --> 10:39.062
Secondly,

10:39.100 --> 10:42.661
it certainly appears
that Mr. Banin ne Andropov

10:42.710 --> 10:45.338
has resigned his position
as a contract killer,

10:45.370 --> 10:47.338
which makes it even more likely

10:47.380 --> 10:49.848
that the victim
is someone that he knew.

10:49.880 --> 10:52.713
These are bereavement cards,
notes from floral arrangements.

10:52.750 --> 10:54.809
You stole these
from Lara's house?
Hmm, yes.

10:54.850 --> 10:57.819
I was hoping
to ascertain which of
Leo's closest associates

10:57.850 --> 11:01.081
had failed to send
their condolences.

11:01.120 --> 11:03.918
Luckily for us, in this case,

11:03.960 --> 11:06.428
_ evidence of absence
is not absence of eVIdence.

11:06.460 --> 11:08.155
Okay, well, if one of his
friends didn't send a card,

11:08.200 --> 11:10.088
it might mean they're dead.

11:10.130 --> 11:12.291
But you don't even know who
his closest associates are.

11:12.330 --> 11:13.888
We know some of them.

11:13.940 --> 11:17.307
His partners
in the nursing home venture--

11:17.340 --> 11:19.934
all but one sent a note.

11:20.980 --> 11:23.141
Travis Hardwick.
It says here that

11:23.180 --> 11:25.774
he is a real estate developer,
but his online CV

11:25.810 --> 11:28.244
strongly suggests he is more
of a small-time contractor

11:28.280 --> 11:29.941
with very poor reviews.

11:29.990 --> 11:31.787
At present,
Mr. Hardwick is

11:31.820 --> 11:34.288
either very difficult
to reach or very dead.

11:35.790 --> 11:38.327
Well, it is 11:00--
it could be that

11:38.360 --> 11:41.090
he may be asleep rather
than in a shallow grave.

11:41.130 --> 11:43.860
I see. Locating this man is
obviously less important to you

11:43.900 --> 11:45.458
than whatever plans
you have this evening.

11:45.500 --> 11:46.990
Unlike you, I have
an official case.

11:47.040 --> 11:48.860
I'm going to the bar
where Jen met that guy.

11:48.900 --> 11:50.834
You're welcome to come.

11:50.870 --> 11:52.770
No. Your friend
would be better off

11:52.810 --> 11:54.437
employing a gigolo
than a private detective.

11:54.480 --> 11:57.142
She'd be amazed how cheaply
a night of anonymous abandon

11:57.180 --> 11:58.807
can be had.
Is she attractive?

11:58.850 --> 12:02.411
I might be able to provide
the service free of charge.

12:02.450 --> 12:04.145
No.

12:04.190 --> 12:06.909
*

12:11.330 --> 12:14.049
Can I get you
something?
Whiskey, neat.

12:15.800 --> 12:17.768
Hey, the guy at the door
said, um,

12:17.800 --> 12:19.427
you've been working here
the longest.

12:19.470 --> 12:21.529
(laughs) Only since birth;
it's my dad's place.

12:21.570 --> 12:23.504
Oh.
What's up?

12:23.540 --> 12:27.237
It's just a friend
of mine met a guy here
about a year ago, so...

12:27.280 --> 12:28.907
Oh, yeah. I think
I remember him.

12:28.940 --> 12:30.908
He likes alcoholic
beverages, right?

12:30.950 --> 12:32.872
Well, I was hoping
he might be a regular here.

12:32.920 --> 12:34.046
His name is Tony.

12:34.080 --> 12:35.411
He's a photojournalist.
Sorry.

12:35.450 --> 12:37.315
What's this all
about, anyway?

12:37.350 --> 12:39.181
Uh, nothing.

12:39.220 --> 12:41.450
Just-- it was a long shot.

12:46.930 --> 12:48.955
*

12:52.430 --> 12:54.398
Hey. Hey!

12:54.440 --> 12:57.068
Um, this place must be
pretty crazy on Brazilian Day,

12:57.110 --> 12:59.066
huh?
What, are you kidding?

12:59.110 --> 13:01.578
Little Brazil is pretty much
just this block, so, like,

13:01.610 --> 13:04.807
half the parade ends up in here
every year, and it's madness.

13:04.850 --> 13:06.818
Uh, thanks.

13:06.850 --> 13:08.408
Thanks. That's really helpful.

13:08.450 --> 13:10.816
SECRETARY:
Here it is.

13:10.850 --> 13:12.283
Hit play.

13:12.320 --> 13:15.517
You can see Leo followed
Travis to his truck that day.

13:15.560 --> 13:16.515
HOLMES:
Your boss' truck--

13:16.560 --> 13:17.822
does it have a LoJack?

13:17.860 --> 13:19.088
I don't think so.

13:19.130 --> 13:20.495
What is it you think
happened to Travis?

13:20.530 --> 13:22.418
We don't know that
anything happened to him.

13:22.460 --> 13:23.961
We just want
to make sure he's okay.

13:24.000 --> 13:25.490
SECRETARY:
Hey. I said you could come in

13:25.530 --> 13:26.838
and see the tape,

13:26.870 --> 13:27.859
not go through his stuff.

13:27.900 --> 13:29.265
If your boss is okay,

13:29.300 --> 13:31.029
I strongly suspect
that he will not notice

13:31.070 --> 13:33.106
his filing system
has been violated.

13:33.140 --> 13:34.232
So, unexpected three-day
absence from work--

13:34.280 --> 13:36.100
did you think
of calling the police?

13:36.140 --> 13:38.301
Clients are in here every month
bitching about something--

13:38.350 --> 13:40.511
the work's slow, there's
money missing, whatever.

13:40.550 --> 13:42.370
Travis pisses a lot
of people off.

13:42.420 --> 13:44.445
Leo was really scary
that day, but Travis

13:44.490 --> 13:46.378
kept saying, "It's under
control, it's under control."

13:46.420 --> 13:49.389
I didn't worry 'cause a little
while later he sent me a text,

13:49.420 --> 13:51.456
said he was headed
to Jersey.
WATSON:
Jersey?

13:51.490 --> 13:54.050
He has an uncle, lives out
in Newark; I figured he went

13:54.100 --> 13:55.397
to borrow more money--
it's happened before.

13:55.430 --> 13:57.068
Well, I'm not so sure
that he sent

13:57.100 --> 13:59.568
that text or that he even went
